Code for my visualizations:
winners <- winners |>
  mutate(year = year(start_date))

winners <- winners |>
  mutate(year_born = year(born)) |>
  mutate(year_died = year(died)) |>
  mutate(lifespan = year_died - year_born)

winners_age <- winners |> group_by(edition, year, winner_name, winner_team) |>
  summarise(winner_age = mean(age))

winners_wins <- winners |> group_by(edition, year, winner_name, winner_team) |>
  summarise(stage_wins = sum(stage_wins))

winners <- winners |> mutate(age_range = case_when(age <= 23 ~ 
                                                           "Young (< 23)",
                                                         age > 23 & age <= 32 ~ 
                                                           "Average (24-32)",
                                                         age > 32 ~ 
                                                           "Old (> 32)"))
age_bracket_count <- winners |> group_by(age_range) |>
  summarise(num = n())

winners_df3 <- winners |>

Abstract

The Tour de France is considered the worldâs most prestigious and difficult bike race. It is an annual stage race consisting of 21 day-long stages over the course of 23 days. The data set used in this project primarily focuses on past Tour de France winners. This refers to the âGeneral Contenderâ or âGCâ winner, which is the rider with the fastest cumulative time over the course of the entire race. The data set contains variables such as: nationality, age, stage wins, and more. I was eager to explore the varying ages of Tour de France winners, and top-performing riders, teams, and countries. I found that the average winner age is 27.7 years old and that the majority of winners (80%) fall in the age range of 24-32. Only 10 winners have been over the age of 32, and about 15 winners under the age of 23. For rider performance, Lance Armstrong is the top-performing rider (7 TDF wins), and France has the most nation and team wins.

Introduction

I found this data set in the Tidy Tuesday repository on github, found here: https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/blob/master/data/2020/2020-04-07/readme.md. Specifically, it comes from Alastair Rushworthâs data package called âtdfâ. The primary data set is called âwinnersâ and contains 106 observations of 19 variables. It covers each edition of the Tour de France, from 1903 up to 2019. The primary variables of interest are winner_name, winner_team, stage_wins, age, and nationality. There is also another data set with more specific stage data, containing 255,752 observations of 11 variables pertaining to stage-specific results in each edition of the Tour de France. I intend looking into the average age of Tour de France winners, and comparing each winnerâs age to their teamâs average age. I will also investigate the top-performing countries, teams, and individual riders (in terms of TDF wins). I will incorporate this into a shiny app with various tabs that answer each of my questions of interest, along with input selections for some of the visualizations. Note: Lance Armstrong is included in this data set, although he has been stripped of his seven Tour de France titles due to doping. There has been widespread doping in cycling, including among Lanceâs competitors.

Visualizations

Note: These are static visuals from my shiny app.

Age Distribution of Tour de France Winners:
ggplot(data = winners_df2, aes(x = year, y = winner_age)) +
  geom_line(colour = "deepskyblue1") +
  geom_point(size = 0.75) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = overall_age, colour = "darkorange", linewidth = 0.5) +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "Age: Tour de France Winners",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Age")

The above graph looks at the varying ages of Tour de France winners across all editions. Age is on the y-axis and year is on the x-axis. Each data point represents the age of a Tour de France winner. The orange horizontal line represents the mean winner age across all editions which is 27.7 years old. We are able to see that the majority of winners fall in the 24 to 32 age range, while there are some winners < 24 and > 32. Although this data set concludes in 2019, it is interesting to note that Tadej PogaÄar won the 2020 Tour de France at the age of 21, and the subsequent year at the age of 22. In the shiny app, this graph is interactive and allows the user to select a Tour de France Winner which will highlight the respective winnerâs data point(s) in red, and update a table that contains other variables like year, age, and stage wins.

Age Comparison between Winner(s) Age and their Teamâs Average Age:

ggplot(data = age_dc, aes(x = reorder(winner_team, team_mean_age), 
                              y = team_mean_age)) +
  geom_point(colour = "red3", size = 6) +
  geom_point(aes(x = winner_name, y = winner_mean_age), 
             colour = "yellow3", size = 6) +
  labs(x = "Name",
       title = "Age Comparison: Winner vs. Team Average",
       y = "Age") +
  theme_classic() +
  ylim(20, 35)

The above graph compares the winnerâs age to their teamâs average age. The y-axis is age and the x-axis is a team with their corresponding winner(s). Note: the team age is calculated as the cumulative average of each teamâs mean rider age from 2000 to 2019. There were limitations with the data so calculating an average was a reasonable alternative. In this particular visual, we are solely looking at Team Discovery Channel, which includes winners Alberto Contador and Lance Armstrong, who won at age 24 and 33 respectively (during 2000-2019 time frame). In most casese, the winnerâs age is consistently within 3 years of their teamâs average age (not in this visualization). In the shiny app, this graph is interactive with plotly and an input selection. The user can select a winning team from 2000 to 2019, and the graph will update with the appropriate team and winner(s). Also, the plotly feature allows the user to hover over the data points which displays the age of the rider or the team average.

Top Riders All-Time:

ggplot(data = rider_wins, aes(x = reorder(winner_name, num_wins), 
                              y = num_wins,

The above graph looks at the top-performing riders of all-time. The x-axis is rider name and the y-axis is number of TDF wins (axes are flipped). Lance Armstrong has won seven titles, followed by four riders who have won five titles, including the legendary Eddy Merckx. In the shiny app, there are radio buttons that allow the user to select one of three different time frames (all-time, first edition to 1974, 1975 to present), which will update the graph with the top-performing riders during those time frames. There is also a plotly feature so that the user can hover to see the number of wins. I didnât want to omit Lance Armstrong from the data because there has been widespread doping in cycling over the years, including among his competitors.

In the early years of the Tour, there was a much higher proportion of French riders in the field; subsequently, more French winners as well. Even in 2023, France had 32 ridersâ more than any other nation. In the shiny app, there is a plotly feature, and radio Buttons that allow the user to select the above graph, or the top-seven performing countries.

Conclusion

Given my questions of interest, I didnât encounter any major limitations in the data or in my visualizations. I found that the average age of a Tour de France winner is 27.7 years old, and the majority of winners fall in the age range of 24 to 32. I also found the top-performing riders (Lance Armstrong), countries (France), and teams (France). When comparing a winnerâs age to their teamâs average, they tend to be within 3 years, with some exceptions. In the future, I would like to see more Tour de France data with rider-specific physiological/output stats. This includes VO2 max, watts per kilogram, resting heart rate, and other variables. This type of data is likely hard to find given that it is personal and changes over time. However, it would be interesting to build a regression model predicting stage wins or Tour de France wins based on certain stats.
